Upgrade 2023 HCM 

SAP provides following project timeline:

Best Practices:

  1. Start with a Sandbox System: Perform a full test upgrade in a non-production system to identify and mitigate issues before the actual upgrade.
  2. Backup Your System: Ensure you have full backups of all systems, including the database and application servers.
  3. Communicate Early: Keep stakeholders informed about downtime, changes, and new features.
  4. Leverage SAP Support: Use SAP’s resources, including support notes and the SAP Help Portal.

 S/4HANA Built-in Tools

  1. SAP HCM | SAP Customer Evolution Kit (formerly value starter / adoption starter now)

1. Planning Phase (Prepare)

This phase involves assessing the readiness of your current system and creating an upgrade plan.

Key Activities:

  1. System Prerequisites Check:
    1. Use the SAP Maintenance Planner to verify compatibility for the upgrade (e.g., hardware, software versions, and required add-ons).
    2.  
  2. Check database and operating system versions. SAP S/4HANA 2023 requires specific database and OS levels, as outlined in the SAP PAM (Product Availability Matrix).

·  Simplification Item Check:

  1. Run the Simplification Item Check tool in your existing system to identify changes and prerequisites in S/4HANA 2023 that may impact business processes or custom code.
  2. Prioritize addressing mandatory changes listed in the Simplification Items.

Accelerator:

  1. (Business Owners) Business-Driven Configuration Assessment questionnaire

2. Custom Code Analysis (Explore)

Custom code compatibility is a critical factor during the upgrade.

Key Activities:

  1. Analyze Custom Code:
    1. Use ABAP Test Cockpit (ATC) or Custom Code Migration App to identify custom code that is incompatible with SAP S/4HANA 2023.
    2. Remediate custom code issues flagged by the analysis (e.g., obsolete or deprecated functions).

Accelerator:

  1. (Business Owners) standard migration templates

  2. Adonis business users documentation (required) 

3. Technical Upgrade Execution (Realize)

This is where the actual upgrade is performed using SAP-provided tools.

Key Activities:

  1. Backup and Sandbox Upgrade:
    1. Create a backup of the current system.
    2. Perform a test upgrade in a sandbox system to identify and resolve issues early.
  2. Software Update Manager (SUM):
    1. Use the SUM (Software Update Manager) tool to upgrade the system.
    2. Choose the appropriate upgrade mode: downtime-optimized or standard mode.
    3. Execute database migration, if required (e.g., migrating to SAP HANA 2.0, if not already on the supported database version).
  3. Apply Add-On Updates:
    1. Update or uninstall add-ons not compatible with SAP S/4HANA 2023, as identified by the Maintenance Planner.

4. Functional Validation (Realize Phase)

After the technical upgrade, validate business processes and ensure all configurations align with S/4HANA 2023 functionalities.

Key Activities:

  1. Regression Testing:
    1. Perform thorough regression testing of critical business processes.
    2. Leverage automation tools like SAP Solution Manager or third-party testing tools.
  2. New Feature Activation:
    1. Evaluate new features and functionalities introduced in S/4HANA 2023.
    2. Perform functional configuration to enable relevant new features (if required).

  3. User Roles and Authorizations as per the best practice in the SAP system.

    1. CRQ000002360954 "AD Cleanup" Robino@swisscom.com / Christian Zwaller (swisscom uptotools) 

    2. Azure AD User type of collaboration (eA4) WinGD 3rd Party 12(X) WinGD 3rd Party 13 - Crosspayroll (Y) EoR (W) External Consultant (V) Collaboration (E) (Z, V,),S, X

    3. for successfactors production ‘Dynamic membership rule’ uses AD PF00_Collaboration (E)   

  4. Unit Testing, String Testing, Integration Testing and User Acceptance Testing

5. Go-Live (Deploy Phase)

Once testing and issue resolution are complete, the system is moved to production.

Key Activities:

  1. Final Downtime Planning:
    1. Minimize downtime by choosing downtime-optimized options in SUM.
  2. Transport to Production:
    1. Transport all upgrade-related changes to the production environment.
  3. Final System Validation:
    1. Perform a final validation of the production system to ensure stability.

6. Post-Go-Live Activities (Run Phase)

After the upgrade, the focus shifts to monitoring, optimization, and user adoption.

  1. Adapting Schemes and Rules

    1. update and customize the relevant time evaluation schemes and rules to be compatible with H4S4.

  2. Migrate IT Infotypes

    migrated obsolete infotypes to the actual ones.

  • phases:

    • Definition of the IT and HR Roadmap

    • Checking the prerequisites for Human Capital Management for S/4HANA

    • Analyzing the legacy SAP ERP HCM system

    • Preparing and getting the SAP ERP HCM system S/4HANA ready

    • Performing the first “dirty migration” to S/4HANA

    • Testing and analyzing the migrated system

    • Fixing functional gaps, custom code etc.

    • Performing the migration of the development system

    • Doing further adaptions

    • Performing the QAS system migration

    • Performing the main tests with HR business team

    • Performing the productive System migration

    • Hypercare & follow-up

Personnel Administration 

Organizational Management 

Objects, Infotypes, and Relationships 

The infotype concept, dynamic actions, features, and the concept of time and payroll calculation rules using operations and functions are unique to HCM; they provide a wide variety of tools that allow you to enhance the standard delivered processes and business process rules within SAP ERP HCM. To enhance existing infotypes to add custom fields, create new custom infotypes, and create custom objects and relationships. 

The PA infotype concept, the technical components that make up an infotype, and the functionality and business logic that reside within the infotype module pool—as well as all infotype-related structures, configuration tables, program objects, BAdIs, customer exits, methods, and features that are included in a specific infotype.
